            <div type="edition"><!-- transcription goes here -->
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/>Θεοῖς <expan><abbr>Καταχθ<hi rend="small">ον</hi></abbr><ex>ίοις</ex></expan>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName><name type="cognomen" key="Onesicrates">Ὀνησικράτου</name>
                    <lb n="3"/><name type="ethnonym" key="Nicomedes">Νεικομηδέος</name></persName>,
                    <lb n="4"/><persName><name type="cognomen" key="Zoilus">Ζωίλος</name></persName> συνπο
                    <lb n="5" break="no"/>λείτης ἐπόησε
                    <lb n="6"/>μνήμης ἕνεκα
                    <lb n="7"/>ὑπὲρ <hi rend="tall">φ</hi>ίλου, <expan><abbr>ζήσαντ</abbr><ex>ος</ex></expan>
                    <lb n="8"/>ἔτη <num value="60">Ξ</num>. Χαίρετε.
                </ab>
            </div>
             
            <div type="commentary"><!-- notes go here -->
            <p>Line 1: small and raised -ον- mark the only abbreviation which expands to complete
                    the plural masculine dative adjective of the common epitaph formula. Line 2/3:
                    ‘Ονησικράτου Νεικομηdέος is attested also in the epitaph in his son Proklos, IG
                    14.876b (=MI.AA.UM.KM.G.1108), also from Misenum and the De Criscio collection.; Νεικομηδεος for
                    Νεικομηδεως. Line 4: Ζωίλος is a fairly common Greek name , presumably his
                    townsman of Nicomedia in Asia minor. Line 7: φίλου is marked by a dot over the
                    upsilon although no other accents or diacritics are indiciated. </p></div>
            
